<font color="#FF0000">GENTLEMEN PART I</font><br>
<tt>Sat Oct 11 20:31:35 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I didn't mean to stir up a hornets nest by posting then appearing to disappear.  I am in competition for the computer, or the phone line with a teen-age daughter who loves to talk both on the phone and in computer chat rooms, as well as a husband who also wants his computer time.  In addition, I have this approach avoidance thingie going on with the whole ball of wax called Vietnam.   Barry,  I didn't stop coming to this site because of anything any of the posters here said.  I was not scared away by anyone. I've been to Nam, I know what these folks are like and despite not having a DD214 I consider myself one of them.  I was, however, getting overwhelmed, obsessing, and not able to continue doing the things that needed to be done at home or work. There are powerful images created here that bring back memories.  Some of us take different times to deal with the shit.  We need to expect that folks may cycle in and out depending on personal stuff, or a need to put some distance from what can still stir up pain if we didn't deal with it totally back when,  even if it has been years.   There is such a thing called timing and pacing oneself.<br><br>
I don't put out my e-mail over open lines not knowing who is lurking or whether some crazy is going to show up in the future and flood my mailbox, or worse knock on my front door.  It is different for a man to go public than a female.  I hope you can respect that reality.  I talked with Doc Del and Doc Spatz via e-mail in the past.  Doc Del because he had a medical role I could identify with and Dr. Spatz cause I couldn't figure out if he was for real or what (sorry Barry)!  Both of them wanted me to post on-line and I just couldn't except in a couple of rare instances.  So, I guess Barry feels a bit protective toward me.  Even Doc Del advised against putting my e-mail address public.  No slight was meant in not contacting others  such as Art, Tom, Chet or Cook who were on-line, made great sense and whose posts have put words to things that have happened in Nam and are helping me to integrate what I consider &quot;a parenthesis in time&quot;.  I just couldn't talk with more of you at the time.  <br><br>
I don't want to &quot;debate&quot; anyone, we should be able to discuss things as friends.  Because we are friends... we should be willing to put up with some inappropriateness now and again.  We can agree to disagree at times and still respect each other. <br><br>
ART:<br><br>
Warrior mode....fight or flight. Not being one to avoid a good argument or take on a just cause,  I can relate to the concept &quot;Provoke me and the consequences flow,&quot;  Art chooses to fight.   Meanest son-of-a-bitch in the valley, eh?  Worked in Nam but not so well stateside. Can get you the label of argumentative at the least.   Take a stand, state one's position but redefending the same ground over and over again with the same arguments against the same arguments is futile.  Personnally having fought many battle of words, I have decided to follow another tact, I now choose my battles. I don't always succeed but I try not to be bullied into fighting something that is just a waste of time to take on in the first place.  No reward even when you win?  Why bother.  <br><br>
You said that tolerance is a &quot;two way street&quot;.  In sitting here considering what you have said, as it relates to Vietnam returnees, it is more of a one way street.  Someone has to make the first move and it is generally us. If the other party says something negative and then your consequences flow, it reinforces preconceptions? It ain't fair, and yes it sucks, but generally the vet is the one who has to prove that they haven't gone off the deep-end from the experience.  It is  true that what we experienced in Vietnam changed us.  We were assimilated into the military society, then into a war time society, and then plunked back into the American civilian society with changed ways (for example always protecting the rear by sitting with our backs against walls. Totally understandable to anyone who served in Nam).  It is we that have returned changed to a society that was not forced to change its cultural way of doing things by the war.  The normal civilian has no comprehension of Vietnam and that our behavior is understandable in relation to what we have been through.  So... what do we do? <br><br>
You raise issues of respect for others, honorable dealings and fair play, genuine debate of differences, and dignity.  Basic human needs.  Is this somehow tied in with your  October 9 post about society chosing not to return to the vet that which was lost. What do you mean by &quot;that which was lost&quot;?  Does that relate to the above paragraph?  How does your statement &quot;To get a feel of what you meant you said one needs to sit in the lobby of any major VA Hospital for a few days&quot; mean.  Can you explain further?  <br><br>
Once you post, if I do not respond immediately please know that it is because I don't go on-line every day  and once I do get your responce  I will ponder and consider what you have said before I get back to you. I am still trying to sift through my feelings on many things related to Vietnam and it just isn't my style to shoot from the hip and then be sorry for what I said.<br><br>
Mustang Two Four (Edward Ramon):<br>
In your post you are doing to me what I have done to others in the past...reading my own personal hurts into something that another said.  Reread what I wrote.  I don't remember saying anything about Spatz being kicked off the site.  He came, he may go.  What went on recently does not seem  to be connected to Spatz as a protesor but more to his need to control. <br><br>
Regarding forgiveness read the last paragraph of my response to SW but please ignor the rest since you don't know or care about my personal investment in Vietnam and I have never been known to impose myself on anyone.  No hard feelings.  <br><br>
SW: <br>
Betrayal is in the eye of the betrayed.  I believe that many of the protestors didn't protest to betray veterans.  Betrayal is a terrible thing....difficult to forgive even when the betrayer is asking for forgiveness and even more so when they aren't.  I don't know whether the protestors are even looking for forgiveness.  I don't believe that most of them think they did anything for which they need to be forgiven. The whole situation with the protests and protestors is extremely complex.<br>
I got orders to Vietnam after Kent State in 1971.  The protests were getting more frequent and the support for the war was virtually gone.  I was working at the Valley Forge Army Hospital spending most of my time working with  men who had lost one or more limbs in Nam and their families.  The men tried  to protect me by telling me not to go. I was dealing day to day with the results of how brutal humans can be during war and the effects of that not only men's bodies but relationships with their families and other loved ones.  But just as many of the men signed up for second tours because they felt they had something special to offer through their experiences and that staying may help to keep some of the new guys alive, I too felt I had something special to offer because of my insight into what one could expect after such wounds and so few were willing to go anymore. <br>
What I found when I arrived in country were thousands and thousands of men dedicated to their country and doing the best within them, but hamstrung by rules and regulation which would never allow them to actually win the war.  How can one be expected to suceed when you had to get approval to fire back on someone who was firing on you.  Frustration levels were out of sight.  In the rear fights were breaking out among our own.  Officers were being killed by their own troops.  Jane Fonda made her now infamous visit to Hanoi and morale hit an all time low.  There seemed to be no end in sight.  I was at the 95th evac hospital which was the closest hospital to the DMZ on the other side of the river from Marble Mtn. outside DaNang.  Sounds of incoming could be heard starting about 11 pm every night.  Snippers around.  Had to get someone to ride shot gun every time we left the compound.  Men were getting hit by mortar rounds, shot, stepping on land mines, getting sick from malaria to the tune of about 100 new admissions each day.  The average stay was 3 days for stabilization and transfer out of country for those who couldn't go back to fight. Some remained long enough to get well and then return to the fighting.  I saw every new admission and those who were still there 6 out of 7 days a week and one of the other Red Cross (RC) women saw the new admission on my day off. ( There were 259 RC hospital workers in Vietnam during the Vietnam era.  We didn't call ourselves Donut Dollies.  About one-fourth  of us were caseworkers, the other therapeutic recreation workers running the hospital recreation centers.  I was a caseworker)   I anticipate that over the 6 months I was at the 95th, before I was transferred to Saigon during the southern attack during the 1972 Easter offensive, I visited and hopefully helped about 4,000 wounded and sick men get in touch with their families, understand and deal with their injuries, and other related duties.   <br><br>
 Since those days I have come to understand something I never understood at the time.  I didn't realize that some/many (I still don't know how prevalent the attitude is)   believed that if not for the  protestors we would have won the war.  I don't know whether we would have won the war or not (I still don't accept that we lost the war...we had a signed treaty, the north broke it).  All I know is that the war was stretching on and on.  Despite the claims that the war was winding down, I was seeing plenty of men injured by that war that supposedly had stopped.  Death and maiming on all sides and for what!   At some point I don't know when, I just wanted us all out.   Damn with saving face. Personally, I believe the protests ultimately is what got us home.  For that I  was thankful even though many were killed after the North took over the South.  There was finally an end to the killing.<br><br>
Now for my reading on protestors.  They come in all shapes and flavors.  Those who were against the Vietnam war.  Those who were against all wars.  Those who were just trying to get out of going themselves. Those who wanted their sons and daughters back.  Unless you talk to them (whoever &quot;they&quot; are), you don't know where &quot;they&quot; were coming from or how far &quot;they&quot; were willing to go.  Not all persons who protested the war went to the extreme of spitting on soldiers.  Those who did won't admit it today.  But if they did spit on you  and admitted they were wrong and asked for forgiveness, would you really refuse to accept that first step toward reconciliation?<br><br>

